ires Province|Jun\u00edn]]||[[Buenos Aires Province|Buenos Aires]]||align=center|1951||[[Sarmiento de Jun\u00edn|Sarmiento (J)]]\n|-\n|43||[[Estadio Fragata Presidente Sarmiento|Fragata Presidente Sarmiento]]||align=center|16,200||[[Isidro Casanova]]||[[Buenos Aires Province|Buenos Aires]]||align=center|1969||[[Club Almirante Brown|Almirante Brown]]\n|-\n|44||Miguel \u00c1ngel Sancho||align=center|15,000||[[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]]||[[C\u00f3rdoba Province (Argentina)|C\u00f3rdoba]]||align=center|1948||[[Racing de C\u00f3rdoba|Racing (C)]]\n|-\n|45||[[Estadio Don Le\u00f3n Kolbowsky|Don Le\u00f3n Kolbowsky]]||align=center|14,000||[[Buenos Aires]]||([[autonomous city]])||align=center|1960||[[Club Atl\u00e9tico Atlanta|Atlanta]]\n|-\n|||[[Estadio Feliciano Gambarte|Feliciano Gambarte]]||align=center|14,000||[[Mendoza, Argentina|Mendoza]]||[[Mendoza Province|Mendoza]]||align=center|1959||[[Godoy Cruz Antonio Tomba|Godoy Cruz]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of association football stadiums by capacity]]\n*[[List of South American stadiums by capacity]]\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.worldstadiums.com/south_america/countries/argentina.shtml World Stadiums \u2013 Stadiums in Argentina]. Retrieved 2010-10-28\n{{Football in Argentina}}\n[[Category:Football venues in Argentina| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of association football stadiums|Argentina]]\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in Argentina|Football stadiums]]\n[[Category:Argentina sport-related lists|Football stadiums]]\n", "name_user": "Brianludden05", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_football_stadiums_in_Argentina"}
{"title_page": "PEN America (journal)", "text_new": "{{Infobox journal\n| title         = PEN America\n| image         = <!-- or |cover= -->\n| caption       = \n| former_name   = <!-- or |former_names= -->\n| abbreviation  = PEN Am.\n| discipline    = [[Literary journal]]\n| language      = English\n| editor        = M. Mark\n| publisher     = [[PEN America]]\n| country       = [[United States]]\n| history       = 2000\u2013present\n| frequency     = Annual\n| openaccess    = \n| license       = \n| impact        = \n| impact-year   = \n| ISSNlabel     = \n| ISSN          = 1536-0261\n| eISSN         = \n| CODEN         = \n| JSTOR         = \n| LCCN          = \n| OCLC          = 47348611\n| website       = http://pen.org/pen-america-journal\n| link1         = \n| link1-name    = \n| link2         = <!-- up to |link5= -->\n| link2-name    = <!-- up to |link5-name= -->\n}}\n\n'''PEN America: A Journal for Writers and Readers''' is an annual literary journal that features fiction, poetry, conversation, criticism, and memoir. It is published by [[PEN America]] in [[New York City]]. Contributors include [[Yousef Al-Mohaimeed]], [[Paul Auster]], [[Michael Cunningham]], [[Lydia Davis]], [[Petina Gappah]], [[Nikki Giovanni]], [[Rawi Hage]], [[Shahriar Mandanipour]], [[Colum McCann]], [[Michael Ondaatje]], [[Marilynne Robinson]], [[Salman Rushdie]], [[Susan Sontag]], [[John Edgar Wideman]], and many others.\n\n== History ==\n''PEN America'' was founded in 2000 by M. Mark, then a member of PEN's Board of Trustees.<ref>[https://pen.org/press-clip/a-literary-night-out-spelling-bee-humiliation/ A Literary Night Out: Spelling Bee Humiliation\u2026] M. Mark is Adjunct Associate Professor of English at [[Vassar College]].[https://www.vassar.edu/faculty/mamark/]</ref> In its first year, PEN America was named one of the \"Ten Best New Magazines\" by [[Library Journal]]. The magazine was nominated for an Utne Independent Press Award for international coverage in 2010.<ref>http://www.utne.com/Media/Nominees-2010-Utne-Independent-Press-Awards.aspx</ref> The essay \"Ghost Writer,\" by [[Cynthia Ozick]], published in [http://www.pen.org/page.php/prmID/1755 PEN America 9: Checkpoints], was reprinted in The Best American Essays 2009 (part of ''[[The Best American Series]]''). Fiction from the magazine has been selected for the [[Pushcart Prize]] in 2009 and 2010.\n\nIn February 2009, [[Edward Albee]], [[Andr\u00e9 Aciman]], [[Anthony Appiah]], [[Ron Chernow]], [[Lydia Davis]], [[Deborah Eisenberg]], [[Francine Prose]], and [[Sarah Ruhl]] participated in the journal's first benefit reading.<ref>https://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/books/2009/02/events-pen-amer.html/</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t3U0hu7aMhQ</ref>\n\n==Issues==\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/1-classics PEN America 1: Classics]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/2-home-away PEN America 2: Home & Away]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/3-tribes PEN America 3: Tribes]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/4-factfiction PEN America 4: Fact/Fiction]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/5-silences PEN America 5: Silences]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/6-metamorphoses PEN America 6: Metamorphoses]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/7-world-voices PEN America 7: World Voices]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/8-making-histories PEN America 8: Making Histories]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/9-checkpoints PEN America 9: Checkpoints]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/10-fear-itself PEN America 10: Fear Itself]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/11-make-believe PEN America 11: Make Believe]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/12-correspondences PEN America 12: Correspondences]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/13-lovers PEN America 13: Lovers]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/14-good-books PEN America 14: The Good Books]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/15-maps PEN America 15: Maps]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/16-teachers PEN America 16: Teachers]\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of literary magazines]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://pen.org/publications/pen-america-a-journal-for-writers-and-readers/ ''PEN America: A Journal for Writers and Readers'' website]\n* [http://penamerica.blogspot.com ''PEN America: A Blog for Writers and Readers'']\n\n[[Category:American literary magazines]]\n[[Category:American annual magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Media in New York City]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox journal\n| title         = PEN America\n| image         = <!-- or |cover= -->\n| caption       = \n| former_name   = <!-- or |former_names= -->\n| abbreviation  = PEN Am.\n| discipline    = [[Literary journal]]\n| language      = English\n| editor        = M. Mark\n| publisher     = [[PEN America]]\n| country       = [[United States]]\n| history       = 2000\u2013present\n| frequency     = Annual\n| openaccess    = \n| license       = \n| impact        = \n| impact-year   = \n| ISSNlabel     = \n| ISSN          = 1536-0261\n| eISSN         = \n| CODEN         = \n| JSTOR         = \n| LCCN          = \n| OCLC          = 47348611\n| website       = http://pen.org/pen-america-journal\n| link1         = \n| link1-name    = \n| link2         = <!-- up to |link5= -->\n| link2-name    = <!-- up to |link5-name= -->\n}}\n\n'''PEN America: A Journal for Writers and Readers''' is an annual literary journal that features fiction, poetry, conversation, criticism, and memoir. It is published by [[PEN America]] in [[New York City]]. Contributors include [[Yousef Al-Mohaimeed]], [[Paul Auster]], [[Michael Cunningham]], [[Lydia Davis]], [[Petina Gappah]], [[Nikki Giovanni]], [[Rawi Hage]], [[Shahriar Mandanipour]], [[Colum McCann]], [[Michael Ondaatje]], [[Marilynne Robinson]], [[Salman Rushdie]], [[Susan Sontag]], [[John Edgar Wideman]], and many others.\n\n== History ==\n''PEN America'' was founded in 2000 by M. Mark, then a member of PEN's Board of Trustees.<ref>[https://pen.org/press-clip/a-literary-night-out-spelling-bee-humiliation/ A Literary Night Out: Spelling Bee Humiliation\u2026] M. Mark is Adjunct Associate Professor of English at [[Vassar College]].[https://www.vassar.edu/faculty/mamark/]</ref> In its first year, PEN America was named one of the \"Ten Best New Magazines\" by [[Library Journal]]. The magazine was nominated for an Utne Independent Press Award for international coverage in 2010.<ref>http://www.utne.com/Media/Nominees-2010-Utne-Independent-Press-Awards.aspx</ref> The essay \"Ghost Writer,\" by [[Cynthia Ozick]], published in [http://www.pen.org/page.php/prmID/1755 PEN America 9: Checkpoints], was reprinted in The Best American Essays 2009 (part of ''[[The Best American Series]]''). Fiction from the magazine has been selected for the [[Pushcart Prize]] in 2009 and 2010.\n\nIn February 2009, [[Edward Albee]], [[Andr\u00e9 Aciman]], [[Anthony Appiah]], [[Ron Chernow]], [[Lydia Davis]], [[Deborah Eisenberg]], [[Francine Prose]], and [[Sarah Ruhl]] participated in the journal's first benefit reading.<ref>https://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/books/2009/02/events-pen-amer.html/</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t3U0hu7aMhQ</ref>\n\n==Issues==\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/1-classics PEN America 1: Classics]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/2-home-away PEN America 2: Home & Away]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/3-tribes PEN America 3: Tribes]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/4-factfiction PEN America 4: Fact/Fiction]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/5-silences PEN America 5: Silences]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/6-metamorphoses PEN America 6: Metamorphoses]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/7-world-voices PEN America 7: World Voices]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/8-making-histories PEN America 8: Making Histories]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/9-checkpoints PEN America 9: Checkpoints]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/10-fear-itself PEN America 10: Fear Itself]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/11-make-believe PEN America 11: Make Believe]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/12-correspondences PEN America 12: Correspondences]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/13-lovers PEN America 13: Lovers]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/14-good-books PEN America 14: The Good Books]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/15-maps PEN America 15: Maps]\n* [http://pen.org/journal-teaser/16-teachers PEN America 16: Teachers]\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of literary magazines]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://pen.org/publications/pen-america-a-journal-for-writers-and-readers/ ''PEN America: A Journal for Writers and Readers'' website]\n* [http://penamerica.blogspot.com ''PEN America: A Blog for Writers and Readers'']\n\n[[Category:American literary magazines]]\n[[Category:Annual magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Media in New York City]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PEN_America_(journal)"}
{"title_page": "Googly", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Short description|Delivery in cricket}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2019}}\n{{about||the 2013 film|Googly (film)||Googly (disambiguation)}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2012}}\n{{Bowling techniques sidebar |expanded=all}}\nIn [[cricket]], a '''googly''' is a type of deceptive [[delivery (cricket)|delivery]] bowled by a right-arm [[leg spin]] [[bowler (cricket)|bowler]]. In [[Australia]], it is usually referred to as a '''wrong'un''', or occasionally as a '''Bosie''' or '''Bosey''', the last two [[eponym]]s in honour of its inventor [[Bernard Bosanquet (cricketer)|Bernard Bosanquet]]. A leg spin bowler bowls in a leg spin way but it goes in the off spin direction.\n\n== Explanation ==\n[[File:Reggie Schwarz c1905.jpg|thumb|right|[[Reggie Schwarz]], known for using the googly as his stock delivery]]\nWhile a normal [[leg break]] spins from the leg to the [[Fielding (cricket)#Off and leg side fields|off side]], away from a right-handed [[batsman]], a googly spins the other side, from off to leg, into a right-handed batsman (and is distinct from an [[off break]] delivery). The bowler achieves this change of spin by bending the wrist sharply from the normal leg break delivery position. When the [[Cricket ball|ball]] rolls out of the hand (from the side near the [[little finger]], as in a normal leg break), it emerges with clockwise spin (from the bowler's point of view). A googly may also be achieved by bowling the ball as a conventional leg break, but spinning the ball further with the fingers just before it is released.<ref name=Warner>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sZ-NIRB28QsC&pg=PA76&lpg=PA76 |title=Cricket |first=Pelham Francis |last=Warner |author-link=Pelham Warner |publisher=[[Longmans, Green, and Company]] |page=76 |year=1920 |access-date=2020-01-17 |via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nThe change of wrist action can be seen by a skilled batsman and the change of spin allowed for when playing a shot at the ball.<ref name=Warner/> Less skilled batsmen, or ones who have lost their concentration, can be deceived completely, expecting the ball to move one direction off the [[Cricket pitch|pitch]], only for it to move the other direction. If the batsman is expecting a leg break, he will play outside the [[line and length|line]] of the ball after it spins. This means the ball can either strike the pads for a potential [[leg before wicket]] (lbw) appeal, or may fly between the bat and the pads and hit the [[wicket]], or catch the edge of the bat.\n\nThe googly is a major weapon in the arsenal of a leg spin bowler, and can be one of the bowler's most effective most important wicket-taking balls. It is used infrequently, because its effectiveness comes mostly from its surprise value.\n\n[[Left-arm unorthodox spin]]ners, commonly known as \"[[Left-arm unorthodox spin|chinaman]]\" bowlers, can bowl with the googly action using the left arm. This delivery is usually known as a chinaman googly and turns away from a right-handed batsman, like a leg break or [[left-arm orthodox spin]]ner. The googly is similar in principle to the [[doosra]], the ball from an [[off-spin]]ner which turns the opposite way from his stock ball.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sportacademy/hi/sa/cricket/skills/newsid_3639000/3639179.stm |title=What is the 'doosra'? |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=2004-08-14 |access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n\n''[[Chambers Dictionary]]'' describes the whole of etymology of the word as \"dubious\".<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pz2ORay2HWoC&lpg=PA692&pg=PA692 |title=The Chambers Dictionary |publisher=[[Allied Chambers]] |isbn=9788186062258 |page=692 |year=1998 |access-date=2020-01-17 |via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n== Mechanics ==\nTo grip the ball for a leg-spinning delivery, the ball is placed into the palm with the seam parallel to the palm. The first two fingers then spread and grip the ball, and the third and fourth fingers close together and rest against the side of the ball. The first bend of the third finger should grasp the seam. The thumb resting against the side is up to the bowler, but should impart no pressure. When the ball is bowled, the third finger will apply most of the spin. The wrist is cocked as it comes down by the hip, and the wrist moves sharply from right to left as the ball is released, adding more spin. The ball is tossed up to provide [[Cricket terminology#F|flight]]. The batsman will see the back of the hand when the ball is released.<ref name=Warner/>\n\n== In popular culture ==\nIn a scene from [[John Boorman]]'s 1987 film ''[[Hope and Glory (film)|Hope and Glory]]'', [[David Hayman]] plays a father who, before leaving to fight in [[World War II|WWII]], passes on \"the secret of the googly\" to his young son.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyscript.com/scripts/hopeandglory.html|title=Hope and Glory|publisher=John Boorman}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Cricket}}\n* [[Carrom ball]]\n* [[Googly problem]]\n* [[Left-arm unorthodox spin]]\n* [[Screwball]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wiktionary}}\n* [https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/skills/4173812.stm Picture and explanation]\n\n[[Category:Bowling (cricket)]]\n[[Category:Cricket terminology]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Short description|Delivery in cricket}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2019}}\n{{For2|the 2013 film|[[Googly (film)]]|other uses|[[Googly (disambiguation)]]}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2012}}\n{{Bowling techniques sidebar |expanded=all}}\nIn [[cricket]], a '''googly''' is a type of deceptive [[delivery (cricket)|delivery]] bowled by a right-arm [[leg spin]] [[bowler (cricket)|bowler]]. In [[Australia]], it is usually referred to as a '''wrong'un''', or occasionally as a '''Bosie''' or '''Bosey''', the last two [[eponym]]s in honour of its inventor [[Bernard Bosanquet (cricketer)|Bernard Bosanquet]]. A leg spin bowler bowls in a leg spin way but it goes in the off spin direction.\n\n== Explanation ==\n[[File:Reggie Schwarz c1905.jpg|thumb|right|[[Reggie Schwarz]], known for using the googly as his stock delivery]]\nWhile a normal [[leg break]] spins from the leg to the [[Fielding (cricket)#Off and leg side fields|off side]], away from a right-handed [[batsman]], a googly spins the other side, from off to leg, into a right-handed batsman (and is distinct from an [[off break]] delivery). The bowler achieves this change of spin by bending the wrist sharply from the normal leg break delivery position. When the [[Cricket ball|ball]] rolls out of the hand (from the side near the [[little finger]], as in a normal leg break), it emerges with clockwise spin (from the bowler's point of view). A googly may also be achieved by bowling the ball as a conventional leg break, but spinning the ball further with the fingers just before it is released.<ref name=Warner>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sZ-NIRB28QsC&pg=PA76&lpg=PA76 |title=Cricket |first=Pelham Francis |last=Warner |author-link=Pelham Warner |publisher=[[Longmans, Green, and Company]] |page=76 |year=1920 |access-date=2020-01-17 |via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nThe change of wrist action can be seen by a skilled batsman and the change of spin allowed for when playing a shot at the ball.<ref name=Warner/> Less skilled batsmen, or ones who have lost their concentration, can be deceived completely, expecting the ball to move one direction off the [[Cricket pitch|pitch]], only for it to move the other direction. If the batsman is expecting a leg break, he will play outside the [[line and length|line]] of the ball after it spins. This means the ball can either strike the pads for a potential [[leg before wicket]] (lbw) appeal, or may fly between the bat and the pads and hit the [[wicket]], or catch the edge of the bat.\n\nThe googly is a major weapon in the arsenal of a leg spin bowler, and can be one of the bowler's most effective most important wicket-taking balls. It is used infrequently, because its effectiveness comes mostly from its surprise value.\n\n[[Left-arm unorthodox spin]]ners, commonly known as \"[[Left-arm unorthodox spin|chinaman]]\" bowlers, can bowl with the googly action using the left arm. This delivery is usually known as a chinaman googly and turns away from a right-handed batsman, like a leg break or [[left-arm orthodox spin]]ner. The googly is similar in principle to the [[doosra]], the ball from an [[off-spin]]ner which turns the opposite way from his stock ball.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sportacademy/hi/sa/cricket/skills/newsid_3639000/3639179.stm |title=What is the 'doosra'? |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=2004-08-14 |access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n\n''[[Chambers Dictionary]]'' describes the whole of etymology of the word as \"dubious\".<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pz2ORay2HWoC&lpg=PA692&pg=PA692 |title=The Chambers Dictionary |publisher=[[Allied Chambers]] |isbn=9788186062258 |page=692 |year=1998 |access-date=2020-01-17 |via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n== Mechanics ==\nTo grip the ball for a leg-spinning delivery, the ball is placed into the palm with the seam parallel to the palm. The first two fingers then spread and grip the ball, and the third and fourth fingers close together and rest against the side of the ball. The first bend of the third finger should grasp the seam. The thumb resting against the side is up to the bowler, but should impart no pressure. When the ball is bowled, the third finger will apply most of the spin. The wrist is cocked as it comes down by the hip, and the wrist moves sharply from right to left as the ball is released, adding more spin. The ball is tossed up to provide [[Cricket terminology#F|flight]]. The batsman will see the back of the hand when the ball is released.<ref name=Warner/>\n\n== In popular culture ==\nIn a scene from [[John Boorman]]'s 1987 film ''[[Hope and Glory (film)|Hope and Glory]]'', [[David Hayman]] plays a father who, before leaving to fight in [[World War II|WWII]], passes on \"the secret of the googly\" to his young son.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyscript.com/scripts/hopeandglory.html|title=Hope and Glory|publisher=John Boorman}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Cricket}}\n* [[Carrom ball]]\n* [[Googly problem]]\n* [[Left-arm unorthodox spin]]\n* [[Screwball]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wiktionary}}\n* [https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/skills/4173812.stm Picture and explanation]\n\n[[Category:Bowling (cricket)]]\n[[Category:Cricket terminology]]\n", "name_user": "Nihiltres", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Simplified hatnote syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Googly"}
{"title_page": "Bison City Stakes", "text_new": "{{Infobox horseraces\n| class         = Restricted\n| horse race    = Bison City Stakes\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| location      = [[Woodbine Racetrack]]<br>[[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| inaugurated   = 1954\n| race type     = [[Thoroughbred]] - [[Flat racing]]\n| website       = {{URL|https://web.archive.org/web/20100316214346/http://www.woodbineentertainment.com:80/qct/default.asp}}\n| distance      = {{frac|1|1|16}} miles (8.5 furlongs)\n| surface       = dirt\n| track         = left-handed\n| qualification = Three-year-old fillies\n| weight        = Scale Weight\n| purse         = $191,725 (2016)\n| bonuses       = \n}}\nThe '''Bison City Stakes''' is a [[Thoroughbred horse race]] run annually at [[Woodbine Racetrack]] in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada.<ref>[http://www.pedigreequery.com/index.php?search_bar=stakes&query_type=stakes&field=view&id=1485 The Bison City Stakes at Pedigree Query]</ref> Held during first week of July, it is open to Canadian-foaled three-year-old [[filly|fillies]]. Since the 1999  creation of the [[Canadian Triple Tiara of Thoroughbred Racing|Canadian Triple Tiara]], the race has been the second leg of the series.<ref>[https://woodbine.com/woodbine-news/enstone-rocks-in-bison-city-stakes/ Woodbine Entertainment Group, July 9, 2017]</ref> It is contested over a distance of {{frac|1|1|16}} miles on [[Polytrack]] synthetic dirt, the race currently offers a purse of $191,725.\n\nThe Bison City Stakes was first run in 1954 at [[Fort Erie Race Track]] in [[Fort Erie, Ontario]]. Since inception it has been contested at two different distances and at two different venues:<ref>{{cite web |title=Woodbine Media Guide (pdf) |url=https://woodbine.com/wp-content/uploads/MediaGuide-ThoroughbredStakesResults-2017.pdf |website=woodbine.com |accessdate=11 April 2020 |page=13}}</ref>\n* {{frac|6|1|2}} furlongs : 1954-1964 at Fort Erie\n* {{frac|1|1|16}} miles : 1965-1976 at Fort Erie, 1977-1979 at [[Woodbine Racetrack]], 1980-2006 at Fort Erie or Woodbine, 2007 to present at Woodbine\n\nIt was run in two divisions in 1956 and 1962. In 1991, [[Francine Villeneuve]] became the first female jockey to win the race. In 2003 there was a [[Tie (draw)|Dead heat]] for first.\n\n==Records==\n'''Speed  record:''' {{small|(Through 1998, Woodbine times were recorded in fifths of a second. Since 1999 they are in hundredths of a second)}}\n* 1:42.15 - [[Awesome Rush]] (2005)\n\n'''Most wins by an owner:'''\n* 7 - [[Sam-Son Farm]] (1972, 1984, 1985, 1987, 1991, 2000, 2003)\n\n'''Most wins by a [[jockey]]:'''\n* 5 - [[Avelino Gomez]] (1959, 1964, 1965, 1967, 1972)\n\n'''Most wins by a [[Horse trainer|trainer]]:'''\n* 4 - [[John Passero]] (1954, 1955, 1957, 1960)\n* 4 - [[James E. Day]] (1984, 1985, 1987, 1991)\n* 4 - [[Roger Attfield]] (1986, 1990, 1993, 2014)\n\n==Winners==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#DACAA5; width:38px\" | Year <br>\n! style=\"background-color:#DACAA5; width:135px\"| Winner <br>\n! style=\"background-color:#DACAA5; width:140px\"| Jockey <br>\n! style=\"background-color:#DACAA5; width:150px\"| Trainer <br>\n! style=\"background-color:#DACAA5; width:170px\"| Owner <br>\n! style=\"background-color:#DACAA5\" | Time\n|-\n|2017\n|Enstone\n|[[Patrick Husbands]]\n|[[Mark E. Casse]]\n| East West Stables\n|1:44.88\n|-\n|2016\n|[[Caren (horse)|Caren]]\n|[[Jesse M. Campbell]]\n|[[Michael P. De Paulo]]\n|Robert Marzilli\n|1:45.47\n|-\n|2015\n|[[Brooklynsway]]\n|[[Emma-Jayne Wilson]]\n|[[John A. Ross (horse trainer)|John A. Ross]]\n|J.R. Racing Stable Inc.\n|1:44:06\n|-\n|2014\n|[[Unspurned]]\n|[[Justin Stein (jockey)|Justin Stein]]\n|[[Roger Attfield]]\n|Christine Hayden\n|1:45.47\n|-\n|2013\n|[[Original Script]]\n|[[Jesse M. Campbell]]\n|[[Paul Attard (horse trainer)|Paul Attard]]\n|Chiefswood Stable\n|1:45.09\n|-\n|2012\n|[[Blue Heart (horse)|Blue Heart]]\n|[[Alex Solis]]\n|[[Brian Lynch (horse trainer)|Brian Lynch]